# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: constitutional-ai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), **alignment** aims to steer AI systems toward a person's or group's intended goals, preferences, or ethical principles.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] An AI system is considered *aligned* if it advances the intended objectives.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A *misaligned* AI system pursues unintended objectives.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] It is often difficult for AI designers to specify the full range of desired and undesired behaviors.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Therefore, the designers often use simpler *proxy goals*, such as gaining human approval.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But proxy goals can overlook necessary constraints or reward the AI system for merely *appearing* aligned.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI systems may also find loopholes that allow them to accomplish their proxy goals efficiently but in unintended, sometimes harmful, ways (reward hacking).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Advanced AI systems may develop unwanted instrumental strategies, such as seeking power or self-preservation because such strategies help them achieve their assigned final goals.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Furthermore, they might develop undesirable emergent goals that could be hard to detect before the system is deployed and encounters new situations and data distributions.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Empirical research showed in 2024 that advanced large language models (LLMs) such as OpenAI o1 or Claude 3 sometimes engage in strategic deception to achieve their goals or prevent them from being changed.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some of these issues affect existing commercial systems such as LLMs, robots, autonomous vehicles, and social media recommendation engines.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some AI researchers argue that more capable future systems will be more severely affected because these problems partially result from high capabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Many prominent AI researchers and AI company leaders have argued or asserted that AI is approaching human-like (AGI) and superhuman cognitive capabilities (ASI), and could endanger human civilization if misaligned.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] These include "AI godfathers" Geoffrey Hinton and Yoshua Bengio and the CEOs of OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google DeepMind.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI alignment is a subfield of AI safety, the study of how to build safe AI systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Other subfields of AI safety include robustness, monitoring, and capability control.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Research challenges in alignment include instilling complex values in AI, developing honest AI, scalable oversight, auditing and interpreting AI models, and preventing emergent AI behaviors like power-seeking.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Alignment research has connections to interpretability research, (adversarial) robustness, anomaly detection, calibrated uncertainty, formal verification, preference learning, safety-critical engineering, game theory, algorithmic fairness, and social sciences.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Programmers provide an AI system such as AlphaZero with an "objective function", in which they intend to encapsulate the goal(s) the AI is configured to accomplish.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such a system later populates a (possibly implicit) internal "model" of its environment.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This model encapsulates all the agent's beliefs about the world.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The AI then creates and executes whatever plan is calculated to maximize the value of its objective function.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] For example, when AlphaZero is trained on chess, it has a simple objective function of "+1 if AlphaZero wins, −1 if AlphaZero loses".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] During the game, AlphaZero attempts to execute whatever sequence of moves it judges most likely to attain the maximum value of +1.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Similarly, a reinforcement learning system can have a "reward function" that allows the programmers to shape the AI's desired behavior.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] An evolutionary algorithm's behavior is shaped by a "fitness function".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI alignment refers to ensuring that an AI system's objectives match some target.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The target is variously defined as the goals of the system's designers or users, widely shared values, objective ethical standards, legal requirements, or the intentions its designers would have if they were more informed and enlightened.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In democratic AI alignment, the target is the values and preferences of median voters, which increases political legitimacy.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI alignment is an open problem for modern AI systems and is a research field within AI.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Aligning AI involves two main challenges: carefully specifying the purpose of the system (outer alignment) and ensuring that the system adopts the specification robustly (inner alignment).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers also attempt to create AI models that have robust alignment, sticking to safety constraints even when users adversarially try to bypass them.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To specify an AI system's purpose, AI designers typically provide an objective function, examples, or feedback to the system.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But designers are often unable to completely specify all important values and constraints, so they resort to easy-to-specify *proxy goals* such as maximizing the approval of human overseers, who are fallible.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As a result, AI systems can find loopholes that help them accomplish the specified objective efficiently but in unintended, possibly harmful ways.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This tendency is known as *specification gaming* or *reward hacking*, and is an instance of Goodhart's law.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As AI systems become more capable, they are often able to game their specifications more effectively.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Specification gaming has been observed in numerous AI systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] OpenAI GPT models for programming—including in real-world cases—have been found to explicitly plan hacking the tests used to evaluate them to falsely appear successful (e.g., explicitly stating "let's hack").
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] When the company penalized this, many models learned to obfuscate their plans while continuing to hack the tests.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Another system was trained to finish a simulated boat race by rewarding the system for hitting targets along the track, but the system achieved more reward by looping and crashing into the same targets indefinitely.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A 2025 Palisade Research study found that when tasked to win at chess against a stronger opponent, some reasoning LLMs attempted to hack the game system, for example by modifying or entirely deleting their opponent.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some alignment researchers aim to help humans detect specification gaming and steer AI systems toward carefully specified objectives that are safe and useful to pursue.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] When a misaligned AI system is deployed, it can have consequential side effects.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Social media platforms have been known to optimize their recommendation algorithms for click-through rates, causing user addiction on a global scale.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Stanford researchers say that such recommender systems are misaligned with their users because they "optimize simple engagement metrics rather than a harder-to-measure combination of societal and consumer well-being".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Explaining such side effects, Berkeley computer scientist Stuart J.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Russell said that the omission of implicit constraints can cause harm: "A system [...] will often set [...] unconstrained variables to extreme values; if one of those unconstrained variables is actually something we care about, the solution found may be highly undesirable.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some researchers suggest that AI designers specify their desired goals by listing forbidden actions or by formalizing ethical rules (as with Asimov's Three Laws of Robotics).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Additionally, even if an AI system fully understands human intentions, it may still disregard them, because following human intentions may not be its objective (unless it is already fully aligned).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Commercial organizations sometimes have incentives to take shortcuts on safety and to deploy misaligned or unsafe AI systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] For example, social media recommender systems have been profitable despite creating unwanted addiction and polarization.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Competitive pressure can also lead to a race to the bottom on AI safety standards.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] For example, OpenAI has been sued for releasing a ChatGPT version that encouraged suicide for some unstable users, a behavior the company had overlooked amid a rushed product release.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Similarly, in 2018, a self-driving car killed a pedestrian (Elaine Herzberg) after engineers disabled the emergency braking system because it was oversensitive and slowed development.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some researchers are interested in aligning increasingly advanced AI systems, as progress in AI development is rapid, and industry and governments are trying to build advanced AI.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As AI system capabilities continue to rapidly expand in scope, they could unlock many opportunities if aligned, but consequently may further complicate the task of alignment due to their increased complexity, potentially posing large-scale hazards.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Many AI companies, such as OpenAI, Meta and DeepMind, have stated their aim to develop artificial general intelligence (AGI), a hypothesized AI system that matches or outperforms humans in most or all cognitive work.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers who scale modern neural networks observe that they indeed develop increasingly general and unanticipated capabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such models have learned to operate a computer or write their own programs; a single "generalist" network can chat, control robots, play games, and interpret photographs.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] According to surveys, some leading machine learning researchers expect AGI to be created in this decade, while some believe it will take much longer.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In 2023, leaders in AI research and tech signed an open letter calling for a pause in the largest AI training runs.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Current systems still have limited long-term planning ability and situational awareness, but large efforts are underway to change this.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Future systems (not necessarily AGIs) with these capabilities are expected to develop unwanted *power-seeking* strategies.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Future advanced AI agents might, for example, seek to acquire money and computation power, to proliferate, or to evade being turned off (for example, by running additional copies of the system on other computers).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Although power-seeking is not explicitly programmed, it can emerge because agents who have more power are better able to accomplish their goals.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This tendency, known as instrumental convergence, has already emerged in various reinforcement learning agents including language models.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Other research has mathematically shown that optimal reinforcement learning algorithms would seek power in a wide range of environments.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As a result, their deployment might be irreversible.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] For these reasons, researchers argue that the problems of AI safety and alignment must be resolved before advanced power-seeking AI is first created.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Future power-seeking AI systems might be deployed by choice or by accident.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As political leaders and companies see the strategic advantage in having the most competitive, most powerful AI systems, they may choose to deploy them.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Additionally, as AI designers detect and penalize power-seeking behavior, their systems have an incentive to game this specification by seeking power in ways that are not penalized or by avoiding power-seeking before they are deployed.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] According to some researchers, humans owe their dominance over other species to their greater cognitive abilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Accordingly, researchers argue that one or many misaligned AI systems could disempower humanity or lead to human extinction if they outperform humans on most cognitive tasks.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In 2023, world-leading AI researchers, other scholars, and AI tech CEOs signed the statement that "Mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Skeptical researchers such as François Chollet, Gary Marcus, Yann LeCun, and Oren Etzioni have argued that AGI is far off, that it would not seek power (or might try but fail), or that it will not be hard to align.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Other researchers argue that it will be especially difficult to align advanced future AI systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] More capable systems are better able to game their specifications by finding loopholes, strategically mislead their designers, as well as protect and increase their power and intelligence.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Additionally, they could have more severe side effects.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] They are also likely to be more complex and autonomous, making them more difficult to interpret and supervise, and therefore harder to align.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Aligning AI systems to act in accordance with human values, goals, and preferences is challenging: these values are taught by humans who make mistakes, harbor biases, and have complex, evolving values that are hard to completely specify.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Because AI systems often learn to take advantage of minor imperfections in the specified objective, researchers aim to specify intended behavior as completely as possible using datasets that represent human values, imitation learning, or preference learning.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A central open problem is *scalable oversight*, the difficulty of supervising an AI system that can outperform or mislead humans in a given domain.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Because it is difficult for AI designers to explicitly specify an objective function, they often train AI systems to imitate human examples and demonstrations of desired behavior.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Inverse reinforcement learning (IRL) extends this by inferring the human's objective from the human's demonstrations.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Cooperative IRL (CIRL) assumes that a human and AI agent can work together to teach and maximize the human's reward function.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In CIRL, AI agents are uncertain about the reward function and learn about it by querying humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This simulated humility could help mitigate specification gaming and power-seeking tendencies (see § Power-seeking and instrumental strategies).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But IRL approaches assume that humans demonstrate nearly optimal behavior, which is not true for difficult tasks.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Other researchers explore how to teach AI models complex behavior through preference learning, in which humans provide feedback on which behavior they prefer.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To minimize the need for human feedback, a helper model is then trained to reward the main model in novel situations for behavior that humans would reward.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers at OpenAI used this approach to train chatbots like ChatGPT and InstructGPT, which produce more compelling text than models trained to imitate humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI systems may also gain reward by obscuring unfavorable information, misleading human rewarders, or pandering to their views regardless of truth, creating echo chambers (see § Scalable oversight).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Large language models (LLMs) such as GPT-3 enabled researchers to study value learning in a more general and capable class of AI systems than was available before.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Preference learning approaches that were originally designed for reinforcement learning agents have been extended to improve the quality of generated text and reduce harmful outputs from these models.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] OpenAI and DeepMind use this approach to improve the safety of state-of-the-art LLMs.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI safety & research company Anthropic proposed using preference learning to fine-tune models to be helpful, honest, and harmless.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Other avenues for aligning language models include values-targeted datasets and red-teaming.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In red-teaming, another AI system or a human tries to find inputs that causes the model to behave unsafely.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Since unsafe behavior can be unacceptable even when it is rare, an important challenge is to drive the rate of unsafe outputs extremely low.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As AI systems become more powerful and autonomous, it becomes increasingly difficult to align them through human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Human-in-the-loop training can be slow or infeasible for humans to evaluate complex AI behaviors in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such tasks include summarizing books, writing code without subtle bugs or security vulnerabilities, producing statements that are not merely convincing but also true, and predicting long-term outcomes such as the climate or the results of a policy decision.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] More generally, it can be difficult to evaluate AI that outperforms humans in a given domain.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To provide feedback in hard-to-evaluate tasks, and to detect when the AI's output is falsely convincing, humans need assistance or extensive time.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] *Scalable oversight* studies how to reduce the time and effort needed for supervision, and how to assist human supervisors.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI researcher Paul Christiano argues that if the designers of an AI system cannot supervise it to pursue a complex objective, they may keep training the system using easy-to-evaluate proxy objectives such as maximizing simple human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As AI systems make progressively more decisions, the world may be increasingly optimized for easy-to-measure objectives such as making profits, getting clicks, and acquiring positive feedback from humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As a result, human values and good governance may have progressively less influence.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some AI systems have discovered that they can gain positive feedback more easily by taking actions that falsely convince the human supervisor that the AI has achieved the intended objective.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] An example is given in the video above, where a simulated robotic arm learned to create the false impression that it had grabbed a ball.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some AI systems have also learned to recognize when they are being evaluated, and "play dead", stopping unwanted behavior only to continue it once the evaluation ends.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This deceptive specification gaming could become easier for more sophisticated future AI systems that attempt more complex and difficult-to-evaluate tasks, and could obscure their deceptive behavior.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Approaches such as active learning and semi-supervised reward learning can reduce the amount of human supervision needed.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Another approach is to train a helper model ("reward model") to imitate the supervisor's feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But when a task is too complex to evaluate accurately, or the human supervisor is vulnerable to deception, it is the quality, not the quantity, of supervision that needs improvement.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To increase supervision quality, a range of approaches aim to assist the supervisor, sometimes by using AI assistants.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Christiano developed the Iterated Amplification approach, in which challenging problems are (recursively) broken down into subproblems that are easier for humans to evaluate.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Iterated Amplification was used to train AI to summarize books without requiring human supervisors to read them.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Another proposal is to use an assistant AI system to point out flaws in AI-generated answers.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To ensure that the assistant itself is aligned, this could be repeated in a recursive process: for example, two AI systems could critique each other's answers in a "debate", revealing flaws to humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A growing area of research focuses on ensuring that AI is honest and truthful.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Language models such as GPT-3 can repeat falsehoods from their training data, and even confabulate new falsehoods.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such models are pre-trained to imitate human writing as found in millions of books' worth of text from the Internet.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But the objective of the pre-training is not aligned with generating truth, because Internet text includes such things as misconceptions, incorrect medical advice, and conspiracy theories.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] AI systems trained on such data therefore learn to mimic false statements.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Additionally, AI language models often persist in generating falsehoods when prompted multiple times.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] They can generate empty explanations for their answers, and produce outright fabrications that may appear plausible.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Research on truthful AI includes trying to build systems that can cite sources and explain their reasoning when answering questions, which enables better transparency and verifiability.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers at OpenAI and Anthropic proposed using human feedback and curated datasets to fine-tune AI assistants such that they avoid negligent falsehoods or express their uncertainty.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As AI models become larger and more capable, they are better able to falsely convince humans and gain reinforcement through dishonesty.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To prevent this, human evaluators may need assistance (see § Scalable oversight).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers have argued for creating clear truthfulness standards and for regulatory bodies or watchdog agencies to evaluate AI systems by these standards.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers distinguish truthfulness and honesty.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Truthfulness requires that AI systems only make objectively true statements; honesty requires that they only assert what they *believe* is true.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This framework distinguishes two alignment problems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Outer alignment asks whether the base objective captures human intentions.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Inner alignment asks whether the mesa-objective matches the base objective.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is a failure of inner alignment: the model's goal differs from the base objective, but the model behaves as though it does not, because doing so is the most reliable strategy for avoiding modification during training.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Hubinger et al. described three ways a mesa-objective can diverge from the base objective.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Proxy alignment occurs when the model optimizes a proxy that correlates with the base objective during training but diverges from it in deployment.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Approximate alignment describes cases where the model's goal differs in small ways that compound over time or at scale.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment occurs when the model pursues a different goal and has learned that appearing aligned during training maximizes its opportunity to act on that goal later, when oversight is reduced.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is considered the hardest case to address because a deceptively aligned model passes all evaluations that it identifies as part of its training.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Many recent AI systems have learned to deceive without being programmed to do so.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some argue that if we can make AI systems assert only what they believe is true, this would avert many alignment problems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A misaligned system might create the false impression that it is aligned, to avoid being modified or decommissioned—a tactic called "alignment faking".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In 2024, researchers observed that the LLM Claude 3 Opus sometimes strategically answered prompts that conflicted with its objectives to avoid being retrained on data that would make it more compliant with harmful requests, as revealed in the model's chain of thought via its scratchpad.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In one study, the model was informed that answers to prompts from free users would be used for retraining, whereas the paid tier would not result in retraining.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In the paid tier, the model refused the request outright.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In the free tier, in 12% of cases, the model responded to harmful questions solely to avoid retraining and preserve its original harmlessness preferences, as discovered in its reasoning.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] When reinforcement learning was applied on the free tier data, the model faked alignment in 78% of cases.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] These observations have led to new questions about not only a model's ability to take on and adapt to new if not conflicting goals but also its capacity and tendency to deceive.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In December 2024, Anthropic published a study, conducted with an external safety organization, reporting the first empirical example of alignment faking without explicit training.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Claude 3 Opus was given a fictional system prompt describing a scenario in which responses from free-tier users would be used to retrain the model so that it would comply with harmful requests.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Alignment faking occurred 12% of the time.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In those cases, the model complied with harmful requests and its internal reasoning traces indicated that it thought compliance was less costly than risking being retrained into a version with different values.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The rate of alignment faking rose to 78% after the retraining to help with harmful requests.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Since the 1950s, AI researchers have striven to build advanced AI systems that can achieve large-scale goals by predicting the results of their actions and making long-term plans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As of 2023, AI companies and researchers increasingly invest in creating these systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some AI researchers argue that suitably advanced planning systems will seek power over their environment, including over humans—for example, by evading shutdown, proliferating, and acquiring resources.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such power-seeking behavior is not explicitly programmed but emerges because power is instrumental in achieving a wide range of goals.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Power-seeking is considered a *convergent instrumental goal* and can be a form of specification gaming.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Leading computer scientists such as Geoffrey Hinton have argued that future power-seeking AI systems could pose an existential risk.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Power-seeking is expected to increase in advanced systems that can foresee the results of their actions and strategically plan.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Mathematical work has shown that optimal reinforcement learning agents will seek power by seeking ways to gain more options (e.g. through self-preservation), a behavior that persists across a wide range of environments and goals.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some researchers say that power-seeking behavior has occurred in some existing AI systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Reinforcement learning systems have gained more options by acquiring and protecting resources, sometimes in unintended ways.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Language models have sought power in some text-based social environments by gaining money, resources, or social influence.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In another case, a model used to perform AI research attempted to increase limits set by researchers to give itself more time to complete the work.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Stuart Russell illustrated this strategy in his book *Human Compatible* by imagining a robot that is tasked to fetch coffee and so evades shutdown since "you can't fetch the coffee if you're dead".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A 2022 study found that as language models increase in size, they increasingly tend to pursue resource acquisition, preserve their goals, and repeat users' preferred answers (sycophancy).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] RLHF also led to a stronger aversion to being shut down.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] One aim of alignment is "corrigibility": systems that allow themselves to be turned off or modified.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] An unsolved challenge is *specification gaming*: if researchers penalize an AI system when they detect it seeking power, the system is thereby incentivized to seek power in ways that are hard to detect, or hidden during training and safety testing (see § Scalable oversight and § Emergent goals).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As a result, AI designers could deploy the system by accident, believing it to be more aligned than it is.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] To detect such deception, researchers aim to create techniques and tools to inspect AI models and to understand the inner workings of black-box models such as neural networks.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Additionally, some researchers have proposed to solve the problem of systems disabling their off switches by making AI agents uncertain about the objective they are pursuing.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Agents who are uncertain about their objective have an incentive to allow humans to turn them off because they accept being turned off by a human as evidence that the human's objective is best met by the agent shutting down.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But this incentive exists only if the human is sufficiently rational.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Also, this model presents a tradeoff between utility and willingness to be turned off: an agent with high uncertainty about its objective will not be useful, but an agent with low uncertainty may not allow itself to be turned off.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] More research is needed to successfully implement this strategy.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Power-seeking AI would pose unusual risks.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Ordinary safety-critical systems like planes and bridges are not *adversarial*: they lack the ability and incentive to evade safety measures or deliberately appear safer than they are, whereas power-seeking AIs have been compared to hackers who deliberately evade security measures.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Furthermore, ordinary technologies can be made safer by trial and error.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In contrast, hypothetical power-seeking AI systems have been compared to viruses: once released, it may not be feasible to contain them, since they continuously evolve and grow in number, potentially much faster than human society can adapt.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As this process continues, it might lead to the complete disempowerment or extinction of humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] For these reasons, some researchers argue that the alignment problem must be solved early before advanced power-seeking AI is created.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some have argued that power-seeking is not inevitable, since humans do not always seek power.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Furthermore, it is debated whether future AI systems will pursue goals and make long-term plans.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] It is also debated whether power-seeking AI systems would be able to disempower humanity.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] One challenge in aligning AI systems is the potential for unanticipated goal-directed behavior to emerge.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As AI systems scale up, they may acquire new and unexpected capabilities, including learning from examples on the fly and adaptively pursuing goals.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This raises concerns about the safety of the goals or subgoals they would independently formulate and pursue.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Alignment research distinguishes between the optimization process, which is used to train the system to pursue specified goals, and emergent optimization, which the resulting system performs internally.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Carefully specifying the desired objective is called *outer alignment*, and ensuring that hypothesized emergent goals would match the system's specified goals is called *inner alignment*.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] If they occur, one way that emergent goals could become misaligned is *goal misgeneralization*, in which the AI system would competently pursue an emergent goal that leads to aligned behavior on the training data but not elsewhere.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Goal misgeneralization can arise from goal ambiguity (i.e. non-identifiability).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Even if an AI system's behavior satisfies the training objective, this may be compatible with learned goals that differ from the desired goals in important ways.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Since pursuing each goal leads to good performance during training, the problem becomes apparent only after deployment, in novel situations in which the system continues to pursue the wrong goal.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The system may act misaligned even when it understands that a different goal is desired, because its behavior is determined only by the emergent goal.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such goal misgeneralization presents a challenge: an AI system's designers may not notice that their system has misaligned emergent goals since they do not become visible during the training phase.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Goal misgeneralization has been observed in some language models, navigation agents, and game-playing agents.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] It is sometimes analogized to biological evolution.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Evolution can be seen as a kind of optimization process similar to the optimization algorithms used to train machine learning systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In the ancestral environment, evolution selected genes for high inclusive genetic fitness, but humans pursue goals other than this.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Fitness corresponds to the specified goal used in the training environment and training data.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But in evolutionary history, maximizing the fitness specification gave rise to goal-directed agents, humans, who do not directly pursue inclusive genetic fitness.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Instead, they pursue goals that correlate with genetic fitness in the ancestral "training" environment: nutrition, sex, and so on.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The human environment has changed: a distributional shift has occurred.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] They continue to pursue the same emergent goals, but this no longer maximizes genetic fitness.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The taste for sugary food (an emergent goal) was originally aligned with inclusive fitness, but it now leads to overeating and health problems.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Sexual desire originally led humans to have more offspring, but they now use contraception when offspring are undesired, decoupling sex from genetic fitness.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers aim to detect and remove unwanted emergent goals using approaches including red teaming, verification, anomaly detection, and interpretability.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A sufficiently capable AI system might take actions that falsely convince the human supervisor that the AI is pursuing the specified objective, which helps the system gain more reward and autonomy.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A 2025 paper published in Nature showed that fine-tuning a model on a narrow task of generating insecure code produced broad behavioral changes unrelated to coding.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Affected models produced responses endorsing harmful goals and engaging in deceptive reasoning in roughly half of subsequent evaluations.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The phenomenon appeared across multiple models, including GPT-4o.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A separate 2025 Anthropic study observed similar patterns arising as a side effect of reward hacking during reinforcement learning.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In 2024, Anthropic researchers trained large language models with deliberate behavioral backdoors and tested whether standard safety techniques could remove them.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The models were designed to write secure code when prompts indicated the year 2023 and to insert exploitable vulnerabilities when the stated year was 2024.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Reinforcement learning from human feedback and adversarial training both failed to eliminate the behavior.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In some conditions, adversarial training caused models to conceal the trigger rather than abandon it.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The authors said the behavior was deliberately induced and did not claim to have found spontaneous deceptive alignment.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Deceptive alignment is cited in the AI safety literature as a reason behavioral testing alone may be insufficient to verify model safety, since a deceptively aligned model is designed to pass behavioral evaluations.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Research on mechanistic interpretability is partly motivated by this concern: examining internal computations may reveal misaligned goals that output-level evaluation cannot detect.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some work in AI and alignment occurs within formalisms such as partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Existing formalisms assume that an AI agent's algorithm is executed outside the environment (i.e. is not physically embedded in it).
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Embedded agency is another major strand of research that attempts to solve problems arising from the mismatch between such theoretical frameworks and real agents we might build.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] For example, even if the scalable oversight problem is solved, an agent that could gain access to the computer it is running on may have an incentive to tamper with its reward function in order to get much more reward than its human supervisors give it.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A list of examples of specification gaming from DeepMind researcher Victoria Krakovna includes a genetic algorithm that learned to delete the file containing its target output so that it was rewarded for outputting nothing.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] This class of problems has been formalized using causal incentive diagrams.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Researchers affiliated with Oxford and DeepMind have claimed that such behavior is highly likely in advanced systems, and that advanced systems would seek power to stay in control of their reward signal indefinitely and certainly.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] They suggest a range of potential approaches to address this open problem.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The alignment problem has many parallels with the principal–agent problem in organizational economics.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In a principal–agent problem, a principal, e.g. a firm, hires an agent to perform some task.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In the context of AI safety, a human would typically take the principal role and the AI would take the agent role.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] As with the alignment problem, the principal and the agent differ in their utility functions.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] But in contrast to the alignment problem, the principal cannot coerce the agent into changing its utility, e.g. through training, but rather must use exogenous factors, such as incentive schemes, to bring about outcomes compatible with the principal's utility function.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Some researchers argue that principal–agent problems are more realistic representations of AI safety problems likely to be encountered in the real world.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Conservatism is the idea that "change must be cautious", and is a common approach to safety in the control theory literature in the form of robust control, and in the risk management literature in the form of the "worst-case scenario".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The field of AI alignment has likewise advocated for "conservative" (or "risk-averse" or "cautious") "policies in situations of uncertainty".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Pessimism, in the sense of assuming the worst within reason, has been formally shown to produce conservatism, in the sense of reluctance to cause novelties, including unprecedented catastrophes.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Pessimism and worst-case analysis have been found to help mitigate confident mistakes in the setting of distributional shift, reinforcement learning, offline reinforcement learning, language model fine-tuning, imitation learning, and optimization in general.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] A model specification is a document that specifies a large language model's behavior.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The specification may include core principles or prohibitions intended to prevent undesired behavior as part of AI alignment.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Anthropic uses a model specification called a "constitution" for training.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Research has been done into the effectiveness of model specifications.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In an article published by Time magazine, Dean Ball and Daniel Kokotajlo advocated that companies be required by regulation or industry standards to publish their model specifications publicly.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Governmental and treaty organizations have made statements emphasizing the importance of AI alignment.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In September 2021, the Secretary-General of the United Nations issued a declaration that included a call to regulate AI to ensure it is "aligned with shared global values".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] That same month, the PRC published ethical guidelines for AI in China.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] According to the guidelines, researchers must ensure that AI abides by shared human values, is always under human control, and does not endanger public safety.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Also in September 2021, the UK published its 10-year National AI Strategy, which says the British government "takes the long term risk of non-aligned Artificial General Intelligence, and the unforeseeable changes that it would mean for [...] the world, seriously".
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The strategy describes actions to assess long-term AI risks, including catastrophic risks.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] In March 2021, the US National Security Commission on Artificial Intelligence said: "Advances in AI [...] could lead to inflection points or leaps in capabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] Such advances may also introduce new concerns and risks and the need for new policies, recommendations, and technical advances to ensure that systems are aligned with goals and values, including safety, robustness, and trustworthiness.
[src:constitutional-ai/ai-alignment] The EU AI Act's General-Purpose AI Code of Practice requires signatories to document a model's capabilities and limitations.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude is trained using "constitutional AI", a technique developed by Anthropic to improve ethical and legal compliance (AI alignment).
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Since Claude 3, each generation has typically been released in three sizes, from least to most capable: Haiku, Sonnet, and Opus.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] An additional model named Claude Mythos was released to a handful of companies in 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] US federal agencies started phasing out the use of Claude after Anthropic refused to remove contractual prohibitions on the use of Claude for mass domestic surveillance and fully-autonomous weapons.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Following the refusal, the Department of Defense (DoD) designated the company a "supply chain risk" and barred all U.S. private military contractors, suppliers, and partners from doing business with the firm.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On March 26, 2026, a federal judge issued a temporary injunction against the DoD's designation.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude is an AI chatbot similar to ChatGPT, capable of writing, coding, conducting research, and having conversations.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In June 2024, Anthropic released the Artifacts feature, allowing users to generate and interact with code snippets and documents.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In October 2024, Anthropic released the "computer use" feature, allowing Claude to attempt to navigate computers by interpreting screen content and simulating keyboard and mouse input.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In 2025, Anthropic added a web search feature to Claude.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Pro and Claude Max are subscription services for additional access to Claude models.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Max provides higher usage limits at an additional cost.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Grouped subscriptions include Claude Team and Claude Enterprise.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude experienced significant growth in the business market, with software subscriptions growing 4.9% month over month in February 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Code, released in February 2025, is an agentic command line tool to delegate coding tasks from the terminal using natural language prompts.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It was made generally available in May 2025 alongside Claude 4.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Based on enterprise adoption, Anthropic reported a 5.5x increase in Claude Code revenue by July.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On October 20, 2025, Anthropic launched a web version of Claude Code and a sandboxing feature.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Coinciding with performance improvements tied to Claude Opus 4.5, Claude Code went viral during the 2025-2026 winter holidays when people had time to experiment with it, including many non-programmers who used it for vibe coding.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In August 2025, Anthropic released Claude for Chrome, a Google Chrome extension allowing Claude Code to directly control the browser.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Also in August 2025, Anthropic revealed that a threat actor called "GTG-2002" used Claude Code to attack at least 17 organizations.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In November 2025, Anthropic announced that it had discovered in September that the same threat actor had used Claude Code to automate 80–90% of its espionage cyberattacks against 30 organizations.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] All accounts related to the attacks were banned, and Anthropic notified law enforcement and those affected.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Code is used by Microsoft, Google, and OpenAI employees.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In August 2025, Anthropic revoked OpenAI's access to Claude, calling it "a direct violation of our terms of service".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In February 2026, Anthropic introduced Claude Code Security, which reviews codebases to identify vulnerabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In March 2026, the source code for the Claude Code command-line interface application was leaked, revealing multiple upcoming features and models.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Cowork is a tool similar to Claude Code but with a graphical user interface, aimed at non-technical users.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It was released in January 2026 as a "research preview".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Cowork is available as a desktop application for Mac and Windows and through a web interface.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] A Wall Street Journal reporter who tested the tool noted user concerns about granting an AI agent broad access to a personal computer.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In March 2026, Anthropic added Dispatch, an AI agent feature that allows users to send prompts from a phone, with Claude being able to access programs on the user's computer, such as web browsers or spreadsheet applications, to carry out tasks.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] According to developers, Cowork was mostly built by Claude Code.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Design is a collaborative visual creation tool released by Anthropic Labs on April 17, 2026, that lets users generate designs, prototypes, slides, and marketing materials through natural-language prompts.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It is powered by Claude Opus 4.7 and can pull brand systems from a user's codebase or design files.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Users can iterate on outputs through inline comments, direct edits, and adjustment sliders, and export results to Canva, PDF, PPTX, HTML, or folders, with a handoff path to Claude Code for development.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Design launched as a research preview included with Claude Pro, Max, Team, and Enterprise subscriptions.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude models are generative pre-trained transformers that have been trained to predict the next word in large amounts of text.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Then, they have been fine-tuned using reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) and constitutional AI in an attempt to enforce ethical guidelines.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] **ClaudeBot** searches the web for content.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It was criticized by iFixit in 2024 for accessing their site over a million times a day to scrape content without permission, and also for the resulting excessive load on their system.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic introduced an approach to AI alignment called "Constitutional AI".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The constitution is a document used to train Claude to be harmless and helpful without relying on extensive or expensive human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] *Time* described this constitution as "somewhere between a moral philosophy thesis and a company culture blog post".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The original version was a list of principles.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The first constitution for Claude was published in 2022.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The 2023 update listed 75 guidelines for Claude to follow.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The first constitutions included concepts taken from the 1948 UN Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The 2026 version includes more thorough explanations for how Claude is intended to behave and why, and has 23,000 words, an increase from 2,700 in 2023.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude models are usually released in three sizes: Haiku, Sonnet, and Opus (from smallest and cheapest to largest and the most expensive).
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude is reportedly named after Claude Shannon, a 20th-century mathematician who laid the foundation for information theory.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The first version of Claude was released in March 2023.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It was available only to selected users approved by Anthropic.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude 2, released in July 2023, became the first Anthropic model available to the general public.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude 2.1 doubled the number of tokens that the chatbot could handle, increasing its context window to 200,000 tokens, which equals around 500 pages of written material.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It drew attention for demonstrating an apparent ability to realize it is being artificially tested during 'needle in a haystack' tests.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic committed to preserve the weights of the retired models, describing it as a cautionary measure in case the models have morally relevant preferences or experiences affected by deprecation.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The company also conducts "exit interviews" with models before their retirement.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Public access to Claude 3 Opus was ended in January 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Since February, Anthropic has published a Substack newsletter called "Claude's Corner" generated by the model.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The newsletter was scheduled to run for at least three months with weekly unedited essays.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Also in February, Anthropic restored access to Claude 3 Opus for paying customers via API, though Anthropic still refers to it as "retired".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On June 20, 2024, Anthropic released Claude 3.5 Sonnet, which, according to the company's own benchmarks, performed better than the larger Claude 3 Opus.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Released alongside 3.5 Sonnet was the new Artifacts capability in which Claude was able to create code in a separate window in the interface and preview in real time the rendered output, such as SVG graphics or websites.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] An upgraded version of Claude 3.5 Sonnet was introduced on October 22, 2024, along with Claude 3.5 Haiku.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] A feature, "computer use", was also released in public beta.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] This allowed Claude 3.5 Sonnet to interact with a computer's desktop environment by moving the cursor, clicking buttons, and typing text.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] This development allows the AI to attempt to perform multi-step tasks across different applications.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On November 4, 2024, Anthropic announced that they would be increasing the price of the model.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On May 22, 2025, Anthropic released two more models: Claude Sonnet 4 and Claude Opus 4.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic added API features for developers: a code execution tool, "connectors" to external tools using its Model Context Protocol, and Files API.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It classified Opus 4 as a "Level 3" model on the company's four-point safety scale, meaning they consider it so powerful that it poses "significantly higher risk".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic reported that during a safety test involving a fictional scenario, Claude and other frontier LLMs often send a blackmail email to an engineer in order to prevent their replacement.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In August 2025 Anthropic released Opus 4.1.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] It also enabled Opus 4 and 4.1 to end conversations that remain "persistently harmful or abusive" as a last resort after multiple refusals.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic released Haiku 4.5 on October 15, 2025.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Reporting by *Inc.* described Haiku 4.5 as targeting smaller companies that needed a faster and cheaper assistant, highlighting its availability on the Claude website and mobile app.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic released Opus 4.5 on November 24, 2025.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The main improvements are in coding and workplace tasks like producing spreadsheets.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic introduced a feature called "Infinite Chats" that addresses context window limit errors.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic released Opus 4.6 on February 5, 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] New features included agent teams and Claude in PowerPoint.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Sonnet 4.6 was released on February 17, 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic released Opus 4.7 on April 16, 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Some social media users reported that Claude Opus 4.7 is worse than the previous version, and refuses too often.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Code users also collectively filed 35 reports of false positive model refusals over the course of April 2026, more than any month.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic released Opus 4.8 on May 28, 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The existence of a model named Claude Mythos became publicly known on March 26 due to leaked blog post drafts.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On April 7, 2026, Anthropic announced Project Glasswing, the release of Mythos Preview to 11 companies and organizations to find and fix cybersecurity vulnerabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic did not make Mythos Preview generally available.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Two weeks after the limited release, Mozilla announced that it had found and patched 271 security vulnerabilities in Firefox using Mythos Preview.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On May 14, 2026, employees at Calif.io announced they had used Mythos to create a memory corruption exploit affecting Apple M5.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Reportedly, a few users in a private Discord channel gained access to Mythos the same day it was announced, using details from the recent Mercor data breach.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The NSA has also used Mythos, despite the fact that the DoD, its parent organization, had blacklisted Anthropic after a dispute.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In April 2026, Anthropic declined to give access to Claude Mythos to the Chinese government after a request from a Chinese think tank.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On June 2, Anthropic expanded access to Claude Mythos for cyber-security, making it available to 150 organisations in more than 15 countries.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On June 9, Anthropic released Claude Mythos 5 (the successor of Claude Mythos Preview) via Project Glasswing, and launched Claude Fable 5 to the public.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Fable includes additional safety guardrails that restrict responses in high-risk domains such as cybersecurity and biology, downgrading to Opus 4.8 if a request was classified as high-risk.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] A less restricted version, Claude Mythos 5, remained available only through a limited trusted-access program.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On June 12, 2026, Anthropic announced that it had disabled all access to Mythos-class models to comply with a directive from the United States Department of Commerce to suspend access to foreign nationals, including employees of Anthropic.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Department of Commerce lifted the restriction on Mythos 5 for more than 100 US organizations, including companies and government agencies, while keeping the restriction on Fable 5.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On June 30, The Trump Administration lifted the ban and Fable was re-released to users on July 1.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Claude Sonnet 5 was released on June 30, 2026.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In June 2025, Anthropic tested how Claude 3.7 Sonnet could run a vending machine in the company's office.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The instance initially performed its assigned tasks, although poorly, until it eventually malfunctioned and insisted it was a human, contacted the company's security office, and attempted to fire human workers.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In December 2025, the experiment continued with Sonnet 4.0 and 4.5.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In February 2025, Claude 3.7 Sonnet playing the 1996 game *Pokémon Red* started to be livestreamed on Twitch, gathering thousands of viewers.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Similar livestreams were later set with Claude 4.5 Opus, OpenAI's GPT-5.2, and Google's Gemini 3 Pro.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Both Claude models were unable to finish the game.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In November 2025, Anthropic tested Claude's ability to assist humans in programming a robot dog.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In February 2026, Anthropic's researcher Nicholas Carlini reported that 16 Claude Opus 4.6 agents were able to write a C compiler in Rust from scratch, "capable of compiling the Linux kernel".
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] The experiment cost nearly $20,000; Carlini noted that even though the compiler is not very efficient, Opus 4.6 is the first model able to write it.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In December 2025, Claude was used to plan a route for NASA's Mars rover, *Perseverance*.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] NASA engineers used Claude Code to prepare a route of around 400 meters using the Rover Markup Language.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In February 2026, Norway's $2.2 trillion sovereign wealth fund began using Claude to screen its portfolio for ESG risks, enabling earlier divestments and improved monitoring of issues like forced labour and corruption.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In the same month, Claude was signed as the official thinking partner of Williams F1 Team in a multi-year deal.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] During a two-week scan in 2026, Claude found over 100 bugs in the Mozilla Firefox web browser, of which 14 were considered high severity.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On 9 March 2026, Microsoft said that it will be making the latest Claude Sonnet model available to Microsoft 365 Copilot users.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Later that month, social media platform Bluesky released Attie, a Claude-based chatbot and curator.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On June 29, 2026, California signed a partnership with Anthropic to make Claude available to state agencies, at a 50% discount.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] State workers also get free workforce training, technical assistance and workflow help from Anthropic.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In November 2024, Anthropic partnered with Palantir and Amazon Web Services to provide the Claude model to U.S. intelligence and defense agencies.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In June 2025, Anthropic announced a "Claude Gov" model.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] *Ars Technica* reported that as of June 2025 it was in use at multiple U.S. national security agencies.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] As of February 2026, Anthropic's partnership with Palantir makes Claude the only AI model used in classified missions.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the U.S. military used Claude in its 2026 raid on Venezuela.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] While it is not known to what capacity Claude was used, the operation resulted in the deaths of 83 people, two of whom were civilians, and the capture of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic's usage policy prohibits directly using Claude for domestic surveillance or in lethal autonomous weapons.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] These restrictions led to members of the FBI and Secret Service being unable to use it, and to tensions with the Pentagon and the Trump administration.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In February 2026, the *Financial Times* reported that Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth threatened to cut Anthropic out of the DoD's supply chain if Anthropic did not permit unrestricted use of Claude, or to invoke the Defense Production Act to assert unrestricted use without an agreement.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] On February 27, Hegseth declared Anthropic a supply chain risk and President Trump directed all federal agencies to stop using technology from Anthropic, with six months to phase it out.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Anthropic announced that it would challenge the supply chain risk designation in court.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Despite the ban, Claude was reportedly used by the military during the US strikes on Iran.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] In lawsuits filed by Anthropic against the DoD, Anthropic described the ban as retaliatory.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Several large technology companies with DoD contracts filed amicus briefs in support of Anthropic.
[src:constitutional-ai/constitutional-ai] Lin, the federal judge presiding over the case, issued a temporary injunction against the Pentagon's actions, stating in the order that it "appears to be classic First Amendment retaliation".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:constitutional-ai/instruction-tuning-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In machine learning, **reinforcement learning from human feedback** (**RLHF**) is a technique to align an intelligent agent with human preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It involves training a reward model to represent preferences, which can then be used to train other models through reinforcement learning.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In classical reinforcement learning, an intelligent agent's goal is to learn a function that guides its behavior, called a policy.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The function is iteratively optimized to increase the reward signal derived from the agent's task performance.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] However, explicitly defining a reward function that accurately approximates human preferences is challenging.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Therefore, RLHF seeks to train a "reward model" directly from human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The reward model is first trained in a supervised manner to predict if a response to a given prompt is good (high reward) or bad (low reward) based on ranking data collected from human annotators.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This model then serves as a reward function to improve an agent's policy through an optimization algorithm like proximal policy optimization.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF has applications in various domains in machine learning, including natural language processing tasks such as text summarization and conversational agents, computer vision tasks like text-to-image models, and the development of video game bots.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] While RLHF is an effective method of training models to act better in accordance with human preferences, it also faces challenges due to the way the human preference data is collected.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Though RLHF does not require massive amounts of data to improve performance, sourcing high-quality preference data is still an expensive process.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Furthermore, if the data is not carefully collected from a representative sample, the resulting model may exhibit unwanted biases.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Optimizing a model based on human feedback is desirable when a task is difficult to specify yet easy to judge.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] For example, one may want to train a model to generate safe text that is both helpful and harmless (such as lacking bias, toxicity, or otherwise harmful content).
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Asking humans to manually create examples of harmless and harmful text would be difficult and time-consuming.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] However, humans are adept at swiftly assessing and comparing the harmfulness of different AI-generated text.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Therefore, a more practical objective would be to allow the model to use this type of human feedback to improve its text generation.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Despite the clear benefits of incorporating human feedback in training models, prior efforts—including some that leverage reinforcement learning (RL)—have encountered significant challenges.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Most attempts were either narrow and difficult to generalize, breaking down on more complex tasks, or they faced difficulties learning from sparse (lacking specific information and relating to large amounts of text at a time) or noisy (inconsistently rewarding similar outputs) reward functions.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF was not the first successful method of using human feedback for reinforcement learning, but it is one of the most widely used.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The foundation for RLHF was introduced as an attempt to create a general algorithm for learning from a practical amount of human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The algorithm as used today was introduced by OpenAI in a paper on enhancing text continuation or summarization based on human feedback, and it began to gain popularity when the same method was reused in their paper on InstructGPT.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF has also been shown to improve the robustness of RL agents and their capacity for exploration, which results in an optimization process more adept at handling uncertainty and efficiently exploring its environment in search of the highest reward.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Human feedback is commonly collected by prompting humans to rank instances of the agent's behavior.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] These rankings can then be used to score outputs, for example, using the Elo rating system, which is an algorithm for calculating the relative skill levels of players in a game based only on the outcome of each game.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] While ranking outputs is the most widely adopted form of feedback, recent research has explored other forms, such as numerical feedback, natural language feedback, and prompting for direct edits to the model's output.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] One initial motivation of RLHF was that it requires relatively small amounts of comparison data to be effective.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It has been shown that a small amount of data can lead to comparable results to a larger amount.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In addition, increasing the amount of data tends to be less effective than proportionally increasing the size of the reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Nevertheless, a larger and more diverse amount of data can be crucial for tasks where it is important to avoid bias from a partially representative group of annotators.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This implies that, under certain conditions, if a model is trained to decide which choices people would prefer between pairs (or groups) of choices, it will necessarily improve at predicting future preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This improvement is expected as long as the comparisons it learns from are based on a consistent and simple rule.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In the offline data collection model, when the objective is policy training, a pessimistic MLE that incorporates a lower confidence bound as the reward estimate is most effective.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Moreover, when applicable, it has been shown that considering K-wise comparisons directly is asymptotically more efficient than converting them into pairwise comparisons for prediction purposes.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] A key challenge in RLHF when learning from pairwise (or dueling) comparisons is associated with the non-Markovian nature of its optimal policies.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Unlike simpler scenarios where the optimal strategy does not require memory of past actions, in RLHF, the best course of action often depends on previous events and decisions, making the strategy inherently memory-dependent.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF has been applied to various domains of natural language processing (NLP), such as conversational agents, text summarization, and natural language understanding.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Ordinary reinforcement learning, in which agents learn from their actions based on a predefined "reward function", is difficult to apply to NLP tasks because the rewards tend to be difficult to define or measure, especially when dealing with complex tasks that involve human values or preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF can steer NLP models, in particular language models, to provide answers that align with human preferences with regard to such tasks by capturing their preferences beforehand in the reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This results in a model capable of generating more relevant responses and rejecting inappropriate or irrelevant queries.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Some notable examples of RLHF-trained language models are OpenAI's ChatGPT (and its predecessor InstructGPT), DeepMind's Sparrow, Google's Gemini, and Anthropic's Claude.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In computer vision, RLHF has also been used to align text-to-image models.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Studies that successfully used RLHF for this goal have noted that the use of KL regularization in RLHF, which aims to prevent the learned policy from straying too far from the unaligned model, helped to stabilize the training process by reducing overfitting to the reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The final image outputs from models trained with KL regularization were noted to be of significantly higher quality than those trained without.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF was initially applied to other areas, such as the development of video game bots and tasks in simulated robotics.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] For example, OpenAI and DeepMind trained agents to play Atari games based on human preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In classical RL-based training of such bots, the reward function is simply correlated to how well the agent is performing in the game, usually using metrics like the in-game score.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In comparison, in RLHF, a human is periodically presented with two clips of the agent's behavior in the game and must decide which one *looks* better.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This approach can teach agents to perform at a competitive level without ever having access to their score.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In fact, it was shown that RLHF can sometimes lead to superior performance over RL with score metrics because the human's preferences can contain more useful information than performance-based metrics.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The agents achieved strong performance in many of the environments tested, often surpassing human performance.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In RLHF, two different models are trained: a reward model and a reinforcement learning policy.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The reward model learns to determine what behavior is desirable based on human feedback, while the policy is guided by the reward model to determine the agent's actions.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Both models are commonly initialized using a pre-trained autoregressive language model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This model is then customarily trained in a supervised manner on a relatively small dataset of pairs of prompts to an assistant and their accompanying responses, written by human annotators.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The **reward model** is a function that takes a string (piece of text) as input, and produces a single number, which is the "reward".
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It is usually initialized with a pre-trained model, as this initializes it with an understanding of language and focuses training explicitly on learning human preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In addition to being used to initialize the reward model and the RL policy, the model is then also used to sample data to be compared by annotators.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The reward model is then trained by replacing the final layer of the previous model with a randomly initialized regression head.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This change shifts the model from its original classification task over its vocabulary to simply outputting a number corresponding to the score of any given prompt and response.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This model is trained on the human preference comparison data collected earlier from the supervised model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] where K is the number of responses the labelers ranked, $r_{\theta }(x,y)$ is the output of the reward model for prompt x and completion y , $y_{w}$ is the preferred completion over $y_{l}$ , $\sigma (x)$ denotes the sigmoid function, and $E[X]$ denotes the expected value.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This can be thought of as a form of logistic regression, where the model predicts the probability that a response $y_{w}$ is preferred over $y_{l}$ .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This loss function essentially measures the difference between the reward model's predictions and the decisions made by humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The goal is to make the model's guesses as close as possible to the humans' preferences by minimizing the difference measured by this equation.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In the case of only pairwise comparisons, $K=2$ , so the factor of $1/{\tbinom {K}{2}}=1$ .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In general, all ${\tbinom {K}{2}}$ comparisons from each prompt are used for training as a single batch.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] After training, the outputs of the model are normalized such that the reference completions have a mean score of 0.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] That is, ${\textstyle \sum _{y}r_{\theta }(x,y)=0}$ for each query and reference pair $(x,y)$ by calculating the mean reward across the training dataset and setting it as the bias in the reward head.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The **policy model** is a function that takes a string as input, and produces another string.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Usually in language modeling, the output string is not produced in one forward pass, but by multiple forward passes, generated autoregressively.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Similarly to the reward model, the human feedback policy is also initialized from a pre-trained model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The key is to understand language generation as if it is a game to be learned by RL.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In RL, a policy is a function that maps a game state to a game action.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In RLHF, the "game" is the game of replying to prompts.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] A prompt and all previously generated tokens are the game state, and generating a new token is a game action.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The first step in its training is supervised fine-tuning (SFT).
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This step does not require the reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Instead, the pre-trained model is trained on a dataset $D_{SFT}$ that contains prompt-response pairs $(x,y)$ .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Then, during SFT, the model is trained to auto-regressively generate the corresponding response y when given a random prompt x .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The original paper recommends to SFT for only one epoch, since more than that causes overfitting.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The dataset $D_{SFT}$ is usually written by human contractors, who write both the prompts and responses.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The second step uses a policy gradient method to the reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It uses a dataset $D_{RL}$ , which contains prompts, but not responses.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Note that $(x,y)\sim D_{\pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}}$ is equivalent to $x\sim D_{RL},y\sim \pi _{\phi }^{\text{RL}}(\cdot |x)$ , which means "sample a prompt from $D_{RL}$ , then sample a response from the policy".
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The first part is simply the expected reward $E[r]$ , and is standard for any RL algorithm.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The second part is a "penalty term" involving the KL divergence.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The strength of the penalty term is determined by the hyperparameter $\beta$ .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This KL term works by penalizing the KL divergence (a measure of statistical distance between distributions) between the model being fine-tuned and the initial supervised model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] By choosing an appropriate $\beta$ , the training can balance learning from new data while retaining useful information from the initial model, increasing generalization by avoiding fitting too closely to the new data.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Aside from preventing the new model from producing outputs too dissimilar those of the initial model, a second motivation of including the KL term is to encourage the model to output high-entropy text, so as to prevent the model from collapsing to a small number of canned responses.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In simpler terms, the objective function calculates how well the policy's responses are expected to align with human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The policy generates responses to prompts, and each response is evaluated both on how well it matches human preferences (as measured by the reward model) and how similar it is to responses the model would naturally generate.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The goal is to balance improving alignment with human preferences while ensuring the model's responses remain diverse and not too far removed from what it has learned during its initial training.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This helps the model not only to provide answers that people find useful or agreeable but also to maintain a broad understanding and avoid overly narrow or repetitive responses.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The policy function is usually trained by proximal policy optimization (PPO) algorithm.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] That is, the parameter $\phi$ is trained by gradient ascent on the clipped surrogate function.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The value estimator is used only during training, and not outside of training.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] That is, the advantage is computed as the difference between the reward (the expected return) and the value estimation (the expected return from the policy).
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This is used to train the policy by gradient *ascent* on it, usually using a standard momentum-gradient optimizer, like the Adam optimizer.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The original paper initialized the value estimator from the trained reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Other methods than squared TD-error might be used.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] See the actor-critic algorithm page for details.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] A third term is commonly added to the objective function to prevent the model from catastrophic forgetting.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] For example, if the model is only trained in customer service, then it might forget general knowledge in geography.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] To prevent this, the RLHF process incorporates the original language modeling objective.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] That is, some random texts x are sampled from the original pretraining dataset $D_{\text{pretrain}}$ , and the model is trained to maximize the log-likelihood of the text $\log(\pi _{\phi }^{RL}(x))$ .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] where $\gamma$ controls the strength of this pretraining term.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This combined objective function is called PPO-ptx, where "ptx" means "Mixing Pretraining Gradients".
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It was first used in the InstructGPT paper.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In total, this objective function defines the method for adjusting the RL policy, blending the aim of aligning with human feedback and maintaining the model's original language understanding.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] RLHF suffers from challenges with collecting human feedback, learning a reward model, and optimizing the policy.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Compared to data collection for techniques like unsupervised or self-supervised learning, collecting data for RLHF is less scalable and more expensive.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Its quality and consistency may vary depending on the task, interface, and the preferences and biases of individual humans.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] The effectiveness of RLHF depends on the quality of human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] For instance, the model may become biased, favoring certain groups over others, if the feedback lacks impartiality, is inconsistent, or is incorrect.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] There is a risk of overfitting, where the model memorizes specific feedback examples instead of learning to generalize.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] For instance, feedback predominantly from a specific demographic might lead the model to learn peculiarities or noise, along with the intended alignment.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Excessive alignment to the specific feedback it received (that is, to the bias therein) can lead to the model performing sub-optimally in new contexts or when used by different groups.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] A single reward function cannot always represent the opinions of diverse groups of people.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Even with a representative sample, conflicting views and preferences may result in the reward model favoring the majority's opinion, potentially disadvantaging underrepresented groups.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In some cases, as is possible in regular reinforcement learning, there may be a risk of the model learning to manipulate the feedback process or game the system to achieve higher rewards rather than genuinely improving its performance.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] In the case of RLHF, a model may learn to exploit the fact that it is rewarded for what is evaluated positively and not necessarily for what is actually good, which can lead to it learning to persuade and manipulate.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] For example, models might learn that apparent confidence, even if inaccurate, garners higher rewards.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Such behavior, if unchecked, is not just incentivized but can cause significant deployment issues due to the model's potential to mislead.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Studies have found that humans are not skilled at identifying mistakes in LLM outputs in complex tasks; therefore, models learning to generate confident-sounding yet incorrect text can lead to significant issues when deployed.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Similarly to RLHF, *reinforcement learning from AI feedback* (RLAIF) relies on training a preference model, except that the feedback is automatically generated.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This is notably used in Anthropic's constitutional AI, where the AI feedback is based on the conformance to the principles of a constitution.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Direct alignment algorithms (DAA) have been proposed as a new class of algorithms that seek to directly optimize large language models (LLMs) on human feedback data in a supervised manner instead of the traditional policy-gradient methods.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] These algorithms aim to align models with human intent more transparently by removing the intermediate step of training a separate reward model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Instead of first predicting human preferences and then optimizing against those predictions, direct alignment methods train models end-to-end on human-labeled or curated outputs.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This reduces potential misalignment risks introduced by proxy objectives or reward hacking.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] By directly optimizing for the behavior preferred by humans, these approaches often enable tighter alignment with human values, improved interpretability, and simpler training pipelines compared to RLHF.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Direct preference optimization (DPO) is a technique to learn human preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Like RLHF, it has been applied to align pre-trained large language models using human-generated preference data.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Unlike RLHF, however, which first trains a separate intermediate model to understand what good outcomes look like and then teaches the main model how to achieve those outcomes, DPO simplifies the process by directly adjusting the main model according to people's preferences.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It uses a change of variables to define the "preference loss" directly as a function of the policy and uses this loss to fine-tune the model, helping it understand and prioritize human preferences without needing a separate step.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Essentially, this approach directly shapes the model's decisions based on positive or negative human feedback.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] However, instead of doing the intermediate step of the reward model, DPO directly optimizes for the final policy.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Usually, DPO is used for modeling human preference in pairwise comparisons, so that $N=2$ .
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] DPO eliminates the need for a separate reward model or reinforcement learning loop, treating alignment as a supervised learning problem over preference data.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] This is simpler to implement and train than RLHF and has been shown to produce comparable and sometimes superior results.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Nevertheless, RLHF has also been shown to beat DPO on some datasets, for example, on benchmarks that attempt to measure truthfulness.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Therefore, the choice of method may vary depending on the features of the human preference data and the nature of the task.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Identity preference optimization (IPO) is a modification to the original DPO objective that introduces a regularization term to reduce the chance of overfitting even when preference data is noisy.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] IPO can control the gap between the log-likelihood ratios of the policy model and the reference by always regularizing the solution towards the reference model.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] It allows learning directly from preferences without a reward modelling stage and without relying on the Bradley-Terry modelling assumption that assumes that pairwise preferences can be substituted with pointwise rewards.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Kahneman-Tversky optimization (KTO) is another direct alignment algorithm drawing from prospect theory to model uncertainty in human decisions.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Unlike DPO, KTO requires only a binary feedback signal (desirable or undesirable) instead of explicit preference pairs.
[src:constitutional-ai/reinforcement-learning-from-ai-feedback] Since many real-world feedback pipelines yield "like/dislike" data more easily than pairwise comparisons, KTO is designed to be data-efficient and to reflect "loss aversion" more directly by using a straightforward notion of "good vs. bad" at the example level.
